fold Character of Panethnicity: Latino Identities and Practices Among Dominicans in New York City -- t12. Immigration Status and Identity: Undocumented Mexicans in New York -- t13. Outside/In: Crossing Queer and Latino Boundaries -- t14. Engendering and Coloring Labor Unions: Transcultural Readings of Latin American Women’s Ways -- tPart IV: Latinizing Cityscapes -- t15. The Latin Side of Madison Avenue: Marketing and the Language that Makes Us "Hispanics" -- t16. Eating in Cuban -- t17. Taking “Class” Into Account: Dance, the Studio, and Latino Culture -- t18. Deceptive Solidity: Public Signs, Civic Inclusion, and Language Rights in New York City (and Beyond)0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew York is the capital of mambo and a global factory of latinidad. This book covers the topic in all its multifaceted aspects, from Jim Crow baseball in the first half of the twentieth century to hip hop and ethno-racial politics, from Latinas and labor unions to advertising and Latino culture, from Cuban cuisine to the language of signs in New York City.Together the articles map out the main conceptions of Latino identity as well as the historical process of Latinization of New York. Mambo Montage is both a way of imagining latinidad and an angle of vision on the city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHispanic AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxEthnic identity. 0aHispanic AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditions. 0aHispanic AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial life and customs. 0aIntercultural communicationzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aPublic spacesxSocial aspectszNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aAponte-Parés, Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu